data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest has dedicated collection and assertion APIs:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 7"* instead of just *"IsTrue failed"*. Expected value goes first.
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** — clearly states what was missing.
- **Message parameters** — give context when `IsTrue` is unavoidable.
- **Removed `users.Count > 0`** — redundant since `AreEqual(3, …)` already covers it.

**Other tools worth knowing:**

| Need | Use |
|---|---|
| Exact elements | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` (order matters) |
| Same items, any order | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` |
| All match type | `CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive))` *(MSTest 3.x+)* |
| Contains item | `CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser)` |

`CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent` is especially useful when you know the expected set but don't care about ordering.
